{"cursor":"8013","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"The 'caloric theory' is an obsolete scientific theory that heat consists of a\nself-repellent fluid called 'caloric' that flows from hotter bodies to colder\nbodies. Caloric was also thought of as a weightless gas that could pass in and\nout of pores in solids and liquids. The \"caloric theory\" was superseded by the\nmid-19th century in favor of the mechanical theory of heat but nevertheless\npersisted in scientific literature until the end of the 19th century. The\n1880 edition of A Guide to the Scientific Knowledge of Things Familiar, a 19th\ncentury educational science book, explained heat transfer in terms of the flow\nof caloric\n","linknr":182,"url":"Caloric_theory","recorded":1362480433,"links":33,"instances":["manufacturing"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Obsolete scientific theories","History of physics","History of chemistry","History of ideas","History of thermodynamics"],"headings":["Early history","Successes","Later developments","Notes","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/35/Ice-calorimeter.jpg/150px-Ice-calorimeter.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/c/c3/Joule%27s_Apparatus_%28Harper%27s_Scan%29.png/220px-Joule%27s_Apparatus_%28Harper%27s_Scan%29.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["boring","manufacturing"]],"members":["boring"],"related":["Obsolete_scientific_theory","Heat","Mechanical_theory_of_heat","Pierre-Simon_Laplace","Heat","Chemical_change","Joseph_Black","Latent_heat","Thermochemistry","History_of_thermodynamics","Combustion","J._J._Becher","Georg_Ernst_Stahl","Phlogiston","Ant